[ctns_make id='axCommuteQ5-2']

    [ctns_question style='width:70%;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;']
TMPL_QUESTIONBLOCK
    [/ctns_question]
    
    [ctns_script type='script']
        var associativity = [
            "%s \cdot %s = %s \cdot %s"
            ];

        var iterations = 10;
        do {
            a = natural();
            b = natural();
        } while (is_gt(iterations--, 0) && a === b);

        symbols.eq = associativity.ctns_rand().ctns_format( [String(a), String(b), String(b), String(a)] );

        q.push(tex({'symbols':symbols, 'reveal':'hide', 'system':'katex'},'
The equation below demonstrates that multiplication for integers is commutative. $| ${eq} |$
')); 
    
        r.push(tex({'symbols':symbols, 'reveal':'hide', 'system':'katex'},'
Multiplication for integers is commutative for any two integers $$a$$ and $$b$$, $|a \cdot b = b \cdot a.|$
')); 

        w.push(tex({'symbols':symbols, 'reveal':'hide', 'system':'katex'},'
To answer this question you must first know the <strong>property of commutativity</strong> for integers under multiplication, which says you can swap the order of multiplication for any two integers $$a$$ and $$b$$ and still get the same sum, $|a \cdot b = b \cdot a.|$ Try this property for yourself using two arbitrary integers $$a$$ and $$b$$.
')); 

        $(qblock).html(q.join(' '));
        $(rightblock).html(r.join(' '));
        $(wrongblock).html(w.join(' '));
        $(undecidedblock).html(w.join(' '));
    [/ctns_script]
    
    [ctns_element type='build_a_graph' swap_a_b='true'][/ctns_element]

[/ctns_make]
